Path Sampling: A Beginners Guide¶

Open Path Sampling (OPS)¶





Open Path Sampling (OPS) is a python library to facilitate path sampling algorithms.

  • Easy to use implementations of many variants of
    • Transition path sampling (TPS)
    • Transition interface sampling (TIS)
    • Committor analysis
    • Flux calculations.
  • Independent of the underlying molecular dynamics engine
    • Currently supports OpenMM & internal engine suitable for 2D toy models

http://www.openpathsampling.org/

Useful links:¶

  • [OPS Installation] (http://openpathsampling.org/latest/install.html#install)
  • [OPS API] (http://openpathsampling.org/latest/api_sections.html)
  • [OPS Tutorials] (http://openpathsampling.org/latest/examples/index.html)
  • [PLUMED Wrapper for OPS] (https://e-cam.readthedocs.io/en/latest/Classical-MD-Modules/modules/OpenPathSampling/ops_plumed_wrapper/readme.html)








PyRETIS is a Python library for rare event molecular simulations with emphasis on methods based on transition interface sampling and replica exchange transition interface sampling.

PyRETIS is open source, easy to use and can be interfaced with other simulation packages such as GROMACS, LAMMPS or CP2K.

http://www.pyretis.org/

Let's Try This¶

A Simple Toy Model¶

First we set up our system: for the toy dynamics, this involves defining a potential energy surface (PES), setting up an integrator, and giving the simulation an initial configuration.

Import¶

In [32]:
# Basic imports
%matplotlib inline
import numpy as np
import openpathsampling as paths

# convenience for the toy dynamics
import openpathsampling.engines.toy as toys

# used for visualization of the 2D toy system
# we use the %run magic because this isn't in a package
%run ./toy_plot_helpers.py

Setup the system¶

First we need to describe the system we'll be simulating.

For the toy model, we need to give a snapshot as a template, as well as a potential energy surface.

[With biomolecular systems, this is often done with an initial PDB structure and a choice of force field.]

PES & Topology¶

In [33]:
# Toy_PES supports adding/subtracting various PESs. 
# The OuterWalls PES type gives an x^6+y^6 boundary to the system.
pes = (toys.OuterWalls([2.0,2.0], [0.0,0.0]) 
       + toys.Gaussian(-0.7, [12.0, 0.5], [-0.5, 0.0])
       + toys.Gaussian(-0.7, [12.0, 0.5], [0.5, 0.0])
#      + toys.Gaussian(0.4, [25, 25], [0.0, 0.3])
      )
# Build topology
topology = toys.Topology(n_spatial=2, masses=[1.0, 1.0], pes=pes)

Plot the PES¶

Now let's look at the potential energy surface we've created:

In [36]:
plot = ToyPlot()
plot.contour_range = np.arange(-1.5, 1.0, 0.1)
plot.add_pes(pes)
fig = plot.plot()

Set up the engine & snapshot¶

The engine needs the template snapshot we set up above, as well as an integrator and a few other options.

In [34]:
# we will use the toy-engine coming with OpenMM
engine = toys.Engine(options={'integ': toys.LangevinBAOABIntegrator(dt=0.02, temperature=0.1, gamma=2.5),
                              'n_frames_max': 5000,
                              'n_steps_per_frame': 10},
                              topology=topology)
In [35]:
template = toys.Snapshot(coordinates=np.array([[0.0, 0.0]]),
                         velocities=np.array([[0.0, 0.0]]),
                         engine=engine)

Define States¶

TPS methods require that you define your states before starting the simulation.

In [37]:
# states are volumes in a CV space: define the CV
def xval(snapshot):
    return snapshot.xyz[0][0]

cv = paths.FunctionCV("xval", xval)

Only take the x coordinate

We define stateA as anything lower than x=-0.5, stateB anything higher than x=0.5

In [38]:
stateA = paths.CVDefinedVolume(cv, float("-inf"), -0.5).named("A")
stateB = paths.CVDefinedVolume(cv, 0.5, float("inf")).named("B")

Plot states¶

In [39]:
plot = ToyPlot()
plot.contour_range = np.arange(-1.5, 1.0, 0.1) # Determines the number and positions of the contour lines / regions
plot.add_pes(pes) 
fig = plot.plot()
ax = fig.gca() # Get the current Axes 
ax.set_ylim(ax.get_ylim())
ax.fill_betweenx(np.linspace(-1.5,1.5),ax.get_xlim()[0],stateA.lambda_max) # "Left" State
ax.fill_betweenx(np.linspace(-1.5,1.5),stateB.lambda_min,ax.get_xlim()[1]) # "Right" State

Prepare path sampling¶

Set up the network and move scheme¶

This is a simple path sampling setup. We use the same TPSNetwork we'll use later for "real" systems, and only one way shooting moves.

In [40]:
# This is important! 
# Here you decide on which kind of path sampling you are going to do
network = paths.TPSNetwork(stateA, stateB)
# Here you decide on which kind of shooting move you are going to use
scheme = paths.OneWayShootingMoveScheme(network, engine=engine)

Getting a first trajectory¶

Path sampling methods require that the user supply an input path for each path ensemble. This means that you must somehow generate a first input path.

This can be quite challenging and not trivial.

Here, however, we will just fake an initial trajectory.

In [41]:
trajectory = paths.Trajectory([
    toys.Snapshot(coordinates=np.array([[-.55+k*0.1, 0.0]]), # You might want to change these
                  velocities=np.array([[0.1, 0.0]]),
                  engine=engine)
    for k in range(12)
])

Prepare initial conditions¶

Create a SampleSet with as many initial samples as possible, make subtrajectories into initial conditions (trajectories become a sampleset)

In [42]:
initial_conditions = scheme.initial_conditions_from_trajectories(trajectory)

No missing ensembles.
No extra ensembles.

Now let's have a look at our system¶

Create storage and simulation object¶

Up to this point, we haven't stored anything in files.

The storage itself is mainly a netCDF file and can also be used as such. (netCDF files are very generic while the OPS Storage is more tuned to needs we have. It supports etc native support for simtk.units)

In [45]:
%rm -f ./resource/toymodel.nc
storage = paths.Storage("./resource/toymodel.nc", "w", template=template)

Create the PathSampling object

In [46]:
simulation = paths.PathSampling(storage, scheme, initial_conditions)

Run the simulation¶

We could simply start the simulation with simulation.run - but wouldn't it be great to see what we are doing?

In [47]:
xval = paths.FunctionCV("xval", lambda snap : snap.xyz[0][0])
yval = paths.FunctionCV("yval", lambda snap : snap.xyz[0][1])
# Visualize the last step of a path sampling simulation using StepVisualizer2D:
simulation.live_visualizer = paths.StepVisualizer2D(network, xval, yval, [-1.0, 1.0], [-1.0, 1.0])
background = ToyPlot()
background.contour_range = np.arange(-1.5, 1.0, 0.1)
background.add_pes(engine.pes)
fig = background.plot()
ax = fig.gca()
ax.set_ylim(ax.get_ylim())
ax.fill_betweenx(np.linspace(-1.5,1.5),ax.get_xlim()[0],stateA.lambda_max)
ax.fill_betweenx(np.linspace(-1.5,1.5),stateB.lambda_min,ax.get_xlim()[1])
simulation.live_visualizer.background = fig
simulation.status_update_frequency = 1 # increasing this number speeds things up, but isn't as pretty

Run our toy system for 100 steps.

In [48]:
simulation.run_until(100)

Okay, now let's start to analyze the contents of our file.

We used a very simple move scheme (only shooting), so the main information that the move_summary gives us is the acceptance of the only kind of move in that scheme.

In [52]:
engine = storage.engines[0]
flex_scheme = storage.schemes[0]
flex_scheme.move_summary(storage.steps) # anything above 30% is considered good, above 50% very good

shooting ran 100.000% (expected 100.00%) of the cycles with acceptance 49/100 (49.00%)

Replica history tree and decorrelated trajectories¶

The ReplicaHistoryTree object gives us both the history tree (often called the "move tree") and the number of decorrelated trajectories.

In [53]:
import openpathsampling.visualize as ops_vis
from IPython.display import SVG
from IPython import display

replica_history = ops_vis.ReplicaEvolution(replica=0)
tree = ops_vis.PathTree(
    storage.steps[0:30],
    replica_history
)
tree.options.css['scale_x'] = 10
In [54]:
# can write to svg file and open with programs that can read SVG
%rm -f ./resource/flex_tps_tree_1.svg
with open("./resource/flex_tps_tree_1.svg", 'w') as f:
    f.write(tree.svg())

We can make things a bit prettier

tree.options.movers['default']['new'] = 'single'

Path length distribution¶

Flexible length TPS gives a distribution of path lengths.

Here we calculate the length of every accepted trajectory, then histogram those lengths, and calculate the maximum and average path lengths.

In [57]:
path_lengths = [len(step.active[0].trajectory) for step in storage.steps]
plt.hist(path_lengths, bins=15, alpha=0.5);
print("Maximum:", max(path_lengths))
print("Average:", "{0:.2f}".format(np.mean(path_lengths)))

Maximum: 30
Average: 16.67

Outlook: A "Real" System¶

Here are the most important steps for running a TPS simulation on alanine dipetide.

We use dihedrals as cvs, and a previously generated trajectory as initial trajectory.

In [ ]:
%matplotlib inline
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import openpathsampling as paths

import openpathsampling.engines.openmm as omm
from simtk.openmm import app
import simtk.openmm as mm
import simtk.unit as unit
from openmmtools.integrators import VVVRIntegrator
import mdtraj as md
import numpy as np

Set up the engine¶

First, we set things up for the OpenMM simulation. We will need a openmm.System object and an openmm.Integrator object.

In [59]:
# this cell is all OpenMM specific
forcefield = app.ForceField('amber96.xml', 'tip3p.xml') # our forcefield & water model
pdb = app.PDBFile("./AD_initial_frame.pdb")   # pdb file of alanine dipeptide
system = forcefield.createSystem(
    pdb.topology, 
    nonbondedMethod=app.PME, 
    nonbondedCutoff=1.0*unit.nanometers,
    constraints=app.HBonds, 
    rigidWater=True,
    ewaldErrorTolerance=0.0005
)
integrator = VVVRIntegrator( # Velocity Verlet with velocity randomization (VVVR) integrator.
    300*unit.kelvin, 
    1.0/unit.picoseconds, 
    2.0*unit.femtoseconds
)
integrator.setConstraintTolerance(0.00001)

engine = omm.Engine(
    template.topology, 
    system, 
    integrator, 
    openmm_properties=openmm_properties,
    options=engine_options
)

engine.name = '300K'

The storage file will need a template snapshot.

In addition, the OPS OpenMM-based Engine has a few properties and options that are set by these dictionaries.

In [ ]:
template = omm.snapshot_from_pdb("./AD_initial_frame.pdb")
openmm_properties = {'OpenCLPrecision': 'mixed'}
engine_options = {
    'n_steps_per_frame': 10,
    'n_frames_max': 2000
}

We load a trajectory we generated previously at high temperature, connecting our two states.

In [ ]:
# without velocities
from openpathsampling.engines.openmm.tools import ops_load_trajectory

traj = ops_load_trajectory("trajectory_file.xtc", top="conf.gro")
In [ ]:
# with velocities we can use MDAnalysis
import mdtraj as md
from openpathsampling.engines.openmm.tools import trajectory_from_mdtraj

mdt = md.load("trajectory_file.trr", top="conf.gro")
# next two lines create numpy array for velocities
trr = md.formats.TRRTrajectoryFile("trajectory_file.trr")
vel = trr._read(n_frames=len(mdt), atom_indices=None, get_velocities=True)[5]
# combine `mdt` and `vel` in an OPS trajectory
traj = trajectory_from_mdtraj(mdt, velocities=vel)

Define The States¶

First we define the CVs using the md.compute_dihedrals function. Then we define our states using PeriodicCVDefinedVolume (since our CVs are periodic.)

In [ ]:
# define the CVs
psi = paths.MDTrajFunctionCV("psi", md.compute_dihedrals, template.topology, indices=[[6,8,14,16]])
phi = paths.MDTrajFunctionCV("phi", md.compute_dihedrals, template.topology, indices=[[4,6,8,14]])
In [ ]:
# define the states
deg = 180.0/np.pi
C_7eq = (
    paths.PeriodicCVDefinedVolume(phi, lambda_min=-180/deg, lambda_max=0/deg, 
                                  period_min=-np.pi, period_max=np.pi) &
    paths.PeriodicCVDefinedVolume(psi, lambda_min=100/deg, lambda_max=200/deg,
                                  period_min=-np.pi, period_max=np.pi)
).named("C_7eq")
# similarly, without bothering with the labels:
alpha_R = (paths.PeriodicCVDefinedVolume(phi, -180/deg, 0/deg, -np.pi, np.pi) &
           paths.PeriodicCVDefinedVolume(psi, -100/deg, 0/deg, -np.pi, np.pi)).named("alpha_R")

Run the TPS¶

As always, the process for setting up a simulation is:

Create a network
Create a move scheme
Set up initial_conditions
Create the PathSampling object and run it.
In [ ]:
network = paths.TPSNetwork(C_7eq, alpha_R)

scheme = paths.OneWayShootingMoveScheme(network, selector=paths.UniformSelector(), engine=engine)

initial_conditions = scheme.initial_conditions_from_trajectories(traj)
In [ ]:
storage_tps = paths.Storage("./resource/alanine_dipeptide_tps.nc", "w", template)
sampler_tps = paths.PathSampling(storage=storage_tps,
                             move_scheme=scheme,
                             sample_set=initial_conditions).named("Flexible_TPS_Sampling")
In [ ]:
#sampler.live_visualizer = paths.StepVisualization2D(network, phi, psi, [-3.14, 3.14], [-3.14, 3.14])
sampler_tps.run(10000)

Now You Should be Ready to Run Your Own TPS Simulation :)¶

Output during simulations:¶

stdout:¶

includes the Monte Carlo step number, the elapsed time, and an estimate of the time remaining.

-> PathSampling.stdout

netCDF:¶

can be read while it is open for writing (analyze while your system is still running)

logging:¶

use the standard Python logging library.

live visualization¶

visualize the last step of a path sampling simulation using StepVisualizer2D:

-> PathSampling.live_visualization
